{"questionId":"14620624","questionHtml":"<p>By using De Moivre’s theorem and your answer to part (a), show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>≡</mo><mn>16</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>5</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>equate imaginary parts:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mn>5</mn><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>5</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>substitute&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>&nbsp;(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><m